##Italian health care resources are scarce and the ICU is not available on a first-come-first-served basis

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

Nan Boyi, _ the_paper _ reporter

On March 10th Italy's "patient 1" was transferred out of the intensive care unit (ICU) , giving a small measure of comfort to the Italian doctors who had been fighting.

Patient one out of the ICU

Lombardy's health department identified patient number one as Mattia, a 38-year-old resident of Codogno and a Unilever worker. After the diagnosis, Mattia was treated at the San Mateo Hospital in Pavia, not far from Milan, where the director of intensive-care unit, Francesco Moyoli, told the Associated Press on the 10th that on the 9th, with only a small amount of oxygen, mattia started breathing on his own, which was a relief. Mattia was then transferred from the intensive-care unit to a intensive-care unit, where he could talk to doctors.

According to the Italian news website Nextquotidiano on February 22, before the onset of symptoms, Mattia ran marathons and other events in towns across northern Italy, where he dined with friends several times. The hospital believes the case has infected at least his pregnant wife, a friend who ran with him and three older locals, the patients often partied at a bar run by Mattia's friend's father. Not only that, he may have infected several staff members and patients at Codogno's local hospital, including a 77 year old woman who died of new pneumonia. Mattia has been called a "super communicator" by several Italian media. After his diagnosis, the Italian government on the 23rd blockaded Lombardy and Veneto, the two regions of 11 towns.

ICU is not a "first come, first served" because resources are scarce

However, Mattia's case also sheds light on Italy's current shortage of health care resources. Doctors are using wartime triage to determine who gets a limited number of ICU beds in Italy's most affected northern region, with an exponential increase in new coronavirus infections, AP reported Monday.

Editor in chief of the paper, Lu Huang, video source: Yang Yi, ITV News

"This is an idea put forward by our colleagues, " said Dr Guido Giustito, President of the Association of Doctors Piedmont in northern Italy, on the 10th, "They don't usually do this under normal circumstances, but it's only because there are so few beds and some people may not have access to medical resources that things are getting more dramatic. "

As of midnight on March 10,1,796 new cases of pneumonia had been reported in Italy, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 9,220, according to the Italian Ministry of Emergency Civil Defense and the News Center on the epidemic A total of 97 new deaths have been recorded, resulting in 463 deaths, with a mortality rate of more than 5% . There have been outbreaks in 99 cities across Italy.

Due to the shortage of ICU during the crisis, the Italian Institute of anesthesiology and intensive care has issued 15 recommendations to inform decisions on transfer to intensive care units, including patients'age and likelihood of survival, the report said, not just "first come, first served. ".

The regional government of Lombardy, the hardest hit region, has been trying to increase the capacity of its intensive care units by converting operating rooms and recovery rooms into isolation rooms for the 440 critically ill patients currently in urgent need of treatment. More than 150 beds have been added temporarily in the past two weeks and another 150 are expected in the coming week.
But it's still not enough.

"unfortunately, we are only at the beginning [ of the outbreak ] , " Dr. Massimo Boutros Boutros-Ghali, director of the Infectious Diseases Department at the SACO hospital in Milan, told Italy's SkyTg24 television, the number of new cases of pneumonia diagnosed by Lombardy last week was similar to the number reported in Wuhan, China, at the end of January. He warned that the figures showed that "the epidemic is likely to spread further" .

Retired doctors and nurses return to the battlefield

According to a report in The Washington Post on March 3, the Italian government has decided to urgently transfer 200,000 medical staff, including nursing students from medical schools, in order to ease the shortage of medical resources, and recalled a number of retired medical staff to the hard-hit areas. Hospitals in priority areas in the north have postponed operations for other non-critical patients and are preparing to increase beds by 50 per cent.

Over the weekend, a nurse named Doris BIA posted on Facebook that she had recently returned to work at Oglio hospital in the devastated city of Cremona after quitting her job to become a full-time mother for several years, AP said. She wrote, starting tomorrow, I will be working with people who are working tirelessly to fight the new coronavirus. "I did it because I couldn't ignore their sacrifice. "

Italian Prime Minister Contes said in a televised speech on the evening of the 9th, in order to avoid further spread of the epidemic, from the 10th to implement a citywide lockdown.
